{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"029b1c88-f347-4f26-9a71-43f19df9f4b6","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) which exposes a `/trace` HTTP endpoint.\n- For a lower-level Linux perf view, `dotnet-trace collect --format speedscope` gives a portable JSON format.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"046245d0-d4fd-4c07-b997-653b35168235","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code change task. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":332,"requestId":"9424:28DE61:18DDF77:1C2A665:69E81E94"},"id":"61da4e10-0ead-4204-913b-b93f585f6206","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:04:28.191Z","parentId":"096b1efc-5890-4301-8afa-5097afc2f29f"}
